    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-01-15T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-01-15T03:00:00-05:00" n="295"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d295">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.51/2722: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_HLW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Henderson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-01-15T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >January 15, 1936—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 15—10:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>21. Last night, at the session of the Central Executive Committee, <persName
                        corresp="#p_GGF1">Grinko</persName> spoke on the budget for the current
                    year. The total budget is 82,900,000,000 rubles. The consolidated state budget
                    is 78,500,000,000 rubles, representing an increase of 21.5 per cent over last
                    year. Military expenditures are to be increased enormously rising from
                    8,200,000,000 rubles in 1935 to 14,800,000,000 rubles this year. Nearly one-half
                    of the total increase falls to purely military items, which will constitute 17.9
                    per cent of the total budget in 1936, as compared with 14.8 per cent last year.
                    Furthermore, many of the expenditures classified as economic (civil aviation,
                    railway construction, capital investment in munitions industries, et cetera) are
                    of course partly military in character.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HLW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Henderson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
